Title: Comparisons of Australian Mental Health Distributions
Author-Name: David Gunawan
Author-X-Name-First: David
Author-X-Name-Last: Gunawan
Author-Email: dgunawan@uow.edu.au
Author-Name: William Griffiths
Author-X-Name-First: William
Author-X-Name-Last: Griffiths  
Author-Email: wegrif@unimelb.edu.au 
Author-Name: Duangkamon Chotikapanich
Author-X-Name-First: Duangkamon
Author-X-Name-Last: Chotikapanich 
Author-Email: duangkamon.chotikapanich@monash.edu 
Keywords: stochastic dominance, Bayesian nonparametric estimation, posterior probabilities,
indigenous population, male and female populations 
Abstract: Bayesian nonparametric estimates of Australian mental health distributions are obtained to 
assess how the mental health status of the population has changed over time, and to compare the 
mental health status of female/male and indigenous/non-indigenous population subgroups. First-order 
and secondorder stochastic dominance are used to compare distributions, with results presented in 
terms of the posterior probability of dominance and the posterior probability of no dominance. If a 
criterion for dominance is satisfied, then, in terms of that criterion, the mental health status of 
the dominant population is superior to that of the dominated population. If neither distribution is 
dominant, then the mental health status of neither population is superior in the same sense. Our 
results suggest mental health has deteriorated in recent years, that males' mental health status 
is better than that of females, and that non-indigenous health status is better than that of the 
indigenous population. 
